<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAWYER IN '54 SCHOOL INTEGRATION CASE DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOPEKA, Kan. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles S. Scott Sr., 67, an attorney who helped integrate public schools 
nationwide by bringing suit in the landmark Brown vs. Topeka Board of Education 
case, died Friday after a long illness following a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
In 1951, Scott, his brother, the late John J. Scott, and the late Charles 
Bledsoe sued the Topeka Board of Education in U.S. District Court on behalf of 
Linda Brown, a black elementary school student. 
</P>
<P>
The case was later appealed to the Supreme Court, which declared on May 17, 
1954, that racial segregation in public schools was unconstitutional. 
</P>
</TEXT>
