<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
INSULIN DOSES HELP CHILDREN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
High doses of insulin appear to at least temporarily prevent the destruction of 
cells in the pancreas that causes the most common form of diabetes among 
children. Researchers at the University of South Florida Health Sciences Center 
in Tampa gave 12 children who had just been diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes four 
times the usual dose of the hormone insulin for two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
Compared to 14 children with Type 1 diabetes who received normal amounts of 
insulin, those who received the intensive insulin appeared to have been spared 
the destruction of cells in the pancreas that produce insulin. 
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 children in the United States have Type 1 or insulin-dependent 
diabetes. The condition is caused by the lack of production of insulin by the 
pancreas. Insulin controls blood sugar levels. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Sharish Shah and his colleagues reported in the New England Journal of 
Medicine that the patients who received the high doses of insulin were 
producing significantly more insulin one year after the treatment than the 14 
children who did not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
